          "body": "The chapter ends with Moses' own exhortatory voice (5:32-33), drawing the logical conclusion from everything that has preceded. The language is total: observe to do just as the LORD your God has commanded you — you shall not turn aside to the right or to the left. The negative form (not turning aside) and the positive form (walk in all the way) are the chapter's final word-pair, and both are necessary. It is possible to avoid gross defection while still drifting incrementally from the covenant path; it is possible to intend the right direction while veering by small degrees. Moses requires both active walking in the full way and disciplined refusal to deviate. The motivation is covenant life: that you may live, that it may be well with you, that you may prolong your days in the land which you will possess (5:33). The three consequences — life, flourishing, longevity — are not the wages of law-keeping earned from a transactional God; they are the blessings of covenant relationship sustained by covenant fidelity. The Deuteronomic connection between obedience and life is not works-righteousness; it is the natural fruit of staying within the covenant framework of a God whose will is always life and whose commands are always for His people's good (Deuteronomy 10:13). The chapter that opened with a summons to hear ends with a summons to walk — the hearing that does not issue in walking has failed."
